@using MobileMvcSamples.Controllers
@{
    ViewBag.Title = "Mobile ASP.NET MVC";
}
    
@helper Status(HomeController.ChapterStatus status)
{
  switch (status)
  {
    case HomeController.ChapterStatus.NotStarted:
      <div class="status not-started">Status: Not started!</div>
      break;
    case HomeController.ChapterStatus.Finished:
      <div class="status finished">Status: Finished!</div>
      break;
    case HomeController.ChapterStatus.InEditing:
      <div class="status editing">Status: In Editing</div>
      break;
    case HomeController.ChapterStatus.InProgress:
      <div class="status in-progress">Status: In Progress</div>
      break;
  }
}

<style>
  .status {
    display: inline-block;
    font-family: monospace;
    font-weight: bold;
    border: solid 1px #ccc;
    padding: 5px 10px;
  }

  .not-started {
    background-color: #ff8a8a;
  }

  .finished {
    background-color: #58c12e;
  }

  .editing {
    background-color: #32a8fe;
  }

  .in-progress {
    background-color: #ffee8f;
  }

  body {
    background-color: #777;
    font-size: 1.2em;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
  }

  .container {
    box-shadow: 4px 0 30px #000;
    background-color: #FFF;
    max-width: 930px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    outline: solid 1px #333;
    padding: 0 15px 15px 15px;
  }

  h1 {
    margin-top: 0;
    padding-top: 20px;
  }

  li {
    margin: 10px 0;
  }

  ol ol li {
    list-style-type: lower-roman;
  }

  ol ol ol li {
    list-style-type: lower-alpha;
  }

  p, li, h4 {
    font-family: Georgia, serif;
  }

  p {
    line-height: 1.4em;
    margin: 0 0 1em 0;
  }

  h1, h2, h3 {
    font-family: Helvetica, Verdana, sans-serif;
  }

  h3 {
    margin: 40px 0 5px 0;
  }

  .callout {
    border: solid 1px #ffd800;
    background-color: #ffee93;
    padding: 15px;
  }

</style>

<div class="container">

  <h1>Mobile ASP.NET MVC</h1>
  <h2>by Eric B. Sowell</h2>

  <img src="/content/book-cover.png" />

  <p>Welcome! This is online home for my book, <i>Mobile ASP.NET MVC</i>, which will be published
    by Apress in Fall of 2013. I&rsquo;ll keep this page up-to-date so you can know my progress and I
    would appreciate any feedback that you have. You can email me at 
    <a href="mailto:eric.sowell@gmail.com">eric.sowell@gmail.com</a>, hit me up on twitter 
    <a href="http://twitter.com/mallioch">@@mallioch</a> or find me
      at my website, <a href="http://ericsowell.com">http://ericsowell.com.</a>
  </p>

  <p class="callout">If you haven&rsquo;t bought the book (why not?), you can buy it 
    <a href="http://www.apress.com/9781430250562">on the Apress website</a> (you can get the alpha
    version now) or <a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1430250569/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=390957&creativeASIN=1430250569&linkCode=as2&tag=thecodhum-20">pre-order it on Amazon</a>.</p>

  <p>This site is primarily for all of my samples in the book that are
    meant to be tested in the browser. Not every chapter has these, so to get all of the samples,
    including these, <a href="https://github.com/Mallioch/MobileMvcSamples">you can get the source 
    code from the Github repository here</a>. Note that <em>some of these samples are not finished</em>,
    though they will all be finished by the time I have written the rough draft of all the chapters.
  </p>

  <p>Note that most of the sub-pages have no styling. This is on purpose since most of the pages are
    meant to be bare examples.
  </p>

  <h2>Chapters</h2>

  <h3>Chapter 1: The Basics of Responsive Web Design</h3>

  @Status(HomeController.ChapterStatus.Finished)

  <p>In this chapter I discuss the basics of Responsive Web Design, which I think is the right place
    to start when starting a new mobile website these days. This chapter is the overview, chapters
    three through five are the deep dive into the approach.
  </p>

  <h4>Samples</h4>
  <ol>
    <li><a href="/responsivebasics/index">Sample responsive site</a></li>
    <li><a href="/responsivebasics/viewportsample">Viewport sample</a></li>
